{"id":"1802.06171","submitter":"Megha Agarwal","authors":"M. Agarwal, E. G. Mishchenko","title":"Potential and spin-exchange interaction between Anderson impurities in\n  graphene","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 99, 085439 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.99.085439","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The effective interaction between resonant magnetic Anderson impurities in\ngraphene, mediated by conduction electrons, is studied as a function of the\nstrength of the onsite energy level of the impurities and the amplitude of\ncoupling to conduction electrons. The sign and character of the interaction\ndepend on whether the impurities reside on the same or opposite sublattices.\nFor the same (opposite) sublattice, the potential interaction is attractive\n(repulsive) in the weak coupling limit with $1/R^3$ dependence on the distance;\nthe interaction reverses sign and becomes repulsive (attractive) in the strong\ncoupling limit and displays $1/R$ behavior. The spin-exchange coupling is\nferromagnetic (antiferromagnetic) at both large and small distances, but\nreverses sign and becomes anti-ferromagnetic (ferromagnetic) for intermediate\ndistances. For opposite sublattices, the effective spin exchange coupling is\nresonantly enhanced at distances where the energy levels cross the Dirac\npoints.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 17 Feb 2018 01:47:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-06"}
